SIMPLE: recommend
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Recommend
<hw>Rec`om*mend"</hw> <pr>(r?k`?m*m?nd")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Recommended</conjf>; <pos>p. pr.
& vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Recommending</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Pref.
<ets>re-</ets> + <ets>commend</ets>: cf. F.
<ets>recommander</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To commend to the
favorable notice of another; to commit to another's care, confidence, or
acceptance, with favoring representations; to put in a favorable light
before any one; to bestow commendation on; <as>as, he
<ex>recommended</ex> resting the mind and exercising the
body</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Maecenas <qex>recommended</qex> Virgil and Horace to Augustus,
whose praises . . . have made him precious to posterity.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make acceptable; to attract favor to.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A decent boldness ever meets with friends,⟦br⟧
Succeeds, and e'en a stranger <qex>recommends</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To commit; to give in charge; to commend.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Paul chose Silas and departed, being <qex>recommended</qex> by the
brethren unto the grace of God.</q> <rj><qau>Acts xv. 40.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Recommendable</ent>⟦br⟧
